  "title": "Toppling Plantations",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9414d642d77ddd42",
      "text": "A child might be perplexed by the regularity of trees planted in columns and rows, each six feet eight inches apart, or the combination of a half-pace and swing of a foresters Pulaski axe when planting the next seedling in what was a meadow about 90 years ago.  A mature forest of mono-cropped red pines seems both unnatural and magical in the same moment.  Riding a bicycle past the long rows plays tricks on the brain as the patterns of sun and shade create an illusion that the forest is moving while the bicyclist is standing still."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c3069e0ea16edbe1",
      "text": "An [[autopoietic]] forest is alive with the potential that comes from many ages of many species of trees, emerging from the complexity of fertile ground.  The red pine plantations transformed meadows into deep beds of pine needles and now, piles of tree trunks, toppled by a combination of age, wind and young boys releasing their frustration with the adult world by pushing standing dead trees back and forth until the shallow roots gave way and the tree fell with a satisfying thud to the needle bed below."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0c41a6ac5b7da6be",
      "text": "Each felled tree represents a disruption to the order of the forest.  It also represents the beginning of a forest re-establishing a long-standing state of autopoiesis.  In the clearings, large and small, new trees became established.  New species of leaves mixed with the pine needles and helped to diversify the soil biology over time.  After 90 years, nearly all of the trees have fallen, or reached the last throes of life on this wind-swept hilltop.  A hybrid forest is emerging, still shaped by the disruption of the meadow, not yet in a natural state of being."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4509e7745ace8f46",
      "text": "One of the many young boys who played in this plantation is now a young man of 25 and has chosen this year to sort out what direction his life might take.  No longer a child, but not yet old enough to learn that life takes us on many adventures, woven together with the adventures of those we meet along the way.  But at this tender age, he has questions. What will his role be in the stewardship of these woodlands, meadows, bogs and plantations?\nWhat types of trees might be planted in the dying plantation?  Does he need to relocate his rough driveway to account for a vacant parcel that will never be developed?  How might he broach this conversation with his aging grandparents? Does he have allies in this journey amongst his siblings, cousins, parents and uncle?\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "84a334ae992a0efe",
      "text": "What does it mean to be self-creating?  Is it possible to be self-creating, or is any organism composed of so many other organisms that a sense of self is always a sense of collective creation?  Does that collective have agency- (as [[Kavita Tanna]] defines it) capacity for awareness, advocacy and action or does this remain a miracle of life-creation? Is consciousness of creation essential or irrelevant? "
    },
